{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01THCKSM6wjTGcAQPPk79FZi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Y9jzww2chJ4NQALfnhqHyR","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) in a contract","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends entirely on what the real AI model understands about contract language and structure. A mocked extractor would always return whatever we tell it to, passing tests even if the real model misses subtle obligation language or non-obvious penalty clauses. Unit tests with stubbed outputs can't verify the model actually finds all terms in documents it hasn't seen before. The failure boundary is the AI model's extraction capability, not the surrounding code.","test_description":"Run the real clause extractor on a curated set of diverse contracts (e.g., NDAs, employment agreements, SLAs, vendor agreements) that contain known key terms. For each contract, verify that extracted parties, dates, obligations, and penalties match a gold standard extracted manually or by legal experts. Include edge cases: abbreviated terms, cross-references, and obligations stated in conditional language (e.g., 'if X occurs, then Y must...'), since real extraction failures often happen on terms the model didn't weight heavily.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test description requires running real AI model to verify term extraction. Mocking the extractor would hide failures where the real model misses terms on unseen contract language.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.95,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Risk assessor flags problematic language even when phrasing is indirect or euphemistic","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Detecting euphemistic language requires semantic understanding that varies across AI models and runs. A mock would always return whatever we program ('yes, this is high risk'), masking failures where the real model fails to recognize indirect phrasing like 'future unspecified costs' or 'at seller's discretion' as problematic. Real models sometimes miss euphemisms on first encounter. Unit tests with mocked outputs can't exercise the model's semantic reasoning on novel phrasings. The failure boundary is the AI model's ability to understand subtle language nuance under the configured risk policy.","test_description":"Create test contracts with language that violates the risk policy in both direct and indirect forms. For example: direct form 'seller may unilaterally increase price' vs. indirect form 'pricing subject to market conditions and seller adjustment'. Run the real risk assessor against both forms and verify both are flagged as high risk. Include euphemisms specific to different contract types (e.g., 'customer responsible for infrastructure costs' in a SaaS contract where it should be seller's responsibility). Log which euphemisms are missed by the real model to inform model tuning.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Requires real AI model running on novel contract language to verify semantic understanding. A mocked assessor would always return the expected flag, hiding real gaps in euphemism detection.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.95,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Compliance checker correctly determines whether a contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Assessing regulatory compliance requires the checker to understand both contract terms and jurisdiction-specific legal requirements. Even if compliance rules are encoded, their application to natural language contract terms depends on semantic understanding. A real failure would be the model misinterpreting a term or missing an implicit compliance gap (e.g., 'seller indemnifies buyer' might not be sufficient under some jurisdictions' consumer protection laws). Mocking the checker with hard-coded 'compliant' or 'non-compliant' responses would hide real gaps in the model's regulatory knowledge or interpretation. The failure boundary is the AI model's understanding of jurisdictional requirements and contract semantics.","test_description":"For each target jurisdiction, construct a test contract that subtly violates one regulatory requirement in a way that's easy for humans to miss but should be caught by the compliance checker (e.g., California privacy: missing required disclosure about third-party data sharing, or New York UCC Article 2: missing specific warranty language). Run the real compliance checker configured for that jurisdiction and verify it flags the violation. Also test a contract that meets all requirements to ensure no false positives. Vary contract language to avoid simple pattern matching (e.g., use different phrasing for the same legal concept).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Testing requires real compliance checker on jurisdiction-specific requirements. Mocking would pass tests even if the real model fails to recognize subtle regulatory gaps in unfamiliar contract structures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments, the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The merge logic itself is deterministic — given two conflicting assessments and a rule for how to combine them, the code either preserves both correctly or doesn't. A unit test with mocked reviewer outputs (e.g., hardcoded JSON objects) can verify the merge algorithm works on expected input formats. However, real failures often come from the actual output structures that the three AI reviewers produce: unexpected field names, missing fields, formatting variations, or nested structures the merge logic wasn't designed to handle. Integration testing wires the real reviewers into the merge step (with real output structures) to catch format mismatches, missing data, or schema evolution bugs that unit tests would miss.","test_description":"Create a test contract where two reviewers reasonably disagree on the same clause (e.g., extractor labels it 'standard indemnity' but risk assessor flags it as 'high-risk unlimited liability'). Run both real reviewers independently on the contract, capture their actual output structures and field names, then feed these outputs into the merge step. Verify the merged report includes both assessments with clear attribution (e.g., 'Extractor: standard indemnity | Risk Assessor: high-risk'). Test edge cases: missing optional fields from one reviewer, different field orderings, and multiple conflicts in the same contract. Verify nothing is dropped or de-duplicated incorrectly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration-level test verifies merge logic handles real output structures from reviewers. A pure unit test with mocked outputs might miss format mismatches that only appear when reviewers run in the real pipeline.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Full pipeline (dispatch to reviewers, collect results, merge) completes correctly on a real contract without losing any reviewer findings","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is an end-to-end test requiring the entire system to operate: dispatching to three real AI reviewers in parallel, collecting their outputs, merging into a unified report. Each of the three reviewers is agentic (depends on real AI model output), and the pipeline orchestrates them in sequence (dispatch → collect → merge). A failure could occur at multiple levels: one reviewer times out and its findings are lost, merge logic drops findings from one reviewer, or the collection step doesn't wait for all three to complete. Unit or integration tests of individual components would miss orchestration failures. Agentic-level testing of single reviewers wouldn't catch issues in coordinating three models. Workflow-level testing exercises the full multi-step agentic pipeline to ensure no findings are lost in the orchestration.","test_description":"Run the full end-to-end pipeline on a real contract with known findings. Manually review the contract beforehand (or use expert annotation) to identify N expected findings across the three reviewers (e.g., 5 key terms, 3 high-risk clauses, 2 compliance issues). Dispatch the contract to all three reviewers simultaneously, wait for all results, merge into the unified report, then verify: (1) all N expected findings are present in the final report, (2) each finding is attributed to the correct reviewer, (3) no findings are duplicated or lost during merge. Repeat on 5–10 diverse real contracts. Include stress cases: contracts that cause one reviewer to take significantly longer, or that trigger edge cases in multiple reviewers simultaneously, to catch timing or ordering bugs in the orchestration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"True end-to-end test with real AI reviewers and orchestration. Lower levels (Unit, Integration, Agentic) can test components in isolation but won't catch orchestration failures or missing findings due to dispatch/collect/merge sequencing issues.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.35,"Workflow":0.5}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13662,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13662},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_